This section of the report analyses association between the variables income (income), sex (sex) with marital status of the respondent (marital.status), number of household members (household.size) and the number of houshold members under 18 (household.under18).

The purpose of this evaluation is to understand how the difference in the income between men and women in the dataset varies across groups with different marital statuses, household sizes and number of household members under 18 and to check for any association between them.

Getting to know our two main variables.

In the previous chunk of code we have appropriately renamed the variables corresponding to sex, race,marital.status, household.size income (as reported on the 2017 survey). Letâs have a quick look at what weâre working with.

From the box plot of marital status and income, we can observe that the median income of the married group is statistically higher than other median income of other groups and for the widowed group it is statistically lower than the median income of other group.

The inter quartile range for the married group is also more than any other group. The range of values for the widowed group is least with no outlierrs, all other groups have significant number of outliers.

We will further create a overlaid histogram to observe the differences and bar graph to see the difference in each group of sex.

In the bar graph we can see that income for male in Never- married and married group is significantly higher than their female counterparts. We do not observe any major difference of income across sex in other groups of marital status.

We will do further analysis to find out more about the association of marital status with income of each sex.

The p-value is significant at the 0 level, so the data suggests that there is an association between income and current marital status. In other words, average income varies across the five groups of marital statuses considered in the data. However we would further like to go ahead and find out if the average income varies across the marital statuses for each sex or not. We add sex variable to our model and are interested to see if there is a statistical dependence between the marital status and sex that impacs the income.

#2 way anova

## 4045 observations deleted due to missingness

We can conclude that both sex and marital status are statistically different from 0. So we can reject the NULL hypothesis and confirm that the marital status has an impact on the income is different for both sex.

Here we carry out a linear model first to see the association of household size with the incom. The p-value is observed to be significant. We therefore go ahead with the multiple linear regression of household size with the income of each sex and interaction between household size and sex. From the summery of multiple linear regression with interaction of income with number of household members and the plot, we can see that there is a significant negative association of the number of household members under 18 with the income. For females the slope of the association is more i.e.Â with the increase in the number of household member under 18, the income of females decreases by -2576.7973266 units more than the males.
